menu "DSP Engine"

    config DSP_ENGINE_DEFAULT_FFT_SIZE
        int "Default FFT size (power of two)"
        default 4096
        range 512 16384
        help
            Default FFT window length in samples. Must be a power of two.
            Larger sizes improve frequency resolution but increase latency
            and PSRAM usage.  4096 gives 11.6 Hz/bin at 48 kHz.

    config DSP_ENGINE_DEFAULT_SAMPLE_RATE
        int "Default sample rate (Hz)"
        default 48000
        help
            Audio sample rate used when the source has not yet negotiated
            a rate.  Must match the I2S or USB audio configuration.

    config DSP_ENGINE_TASK_STACK_SIZE
        int "DSP engine task stack size (bytes)"
        default 8192
        help
            Stack depth for the FreeRTOS DSP processing task.  The task
            uses floating-point math so it needs at least 6 KB.

    config DSP_ENGINE_TASK_PRIORITY
        int "DSP engine task priority"
        default 20
        range 1 24
        help
            FreeRTOS priority for the DSP task.  Should be below the audio
            capture task (22) but above the UI update task (7).

    config DSP_ENGINE_TASK_CORE
        int "DSP engine task CPU core"
        default 1
        range 0 1
        help
            CPU core affinity for the DSP task.  Core 1 is preferred to
            leave core 0 for the LVGL port task and UI updates.

    config DSP_ENGINE_RING_BUF_MULTIPLIER
        int "Ring buffer size multiplier (× FFT size)"
        default 4
        range 2 8
        help
            The ring buffer between the audio capture task and the DSP task
            is allocated as (multiplier × fft_size × sizeof(int16_t)) bytes.
            4× provides enough depth to absorb scheduling jitter at 48 kHz
            without stalling the USB or I2S DMA.

    config DSP_ENGINE_FRAME_POOL_SIZE
        int "Number of pre-allocated output frame slots"
        default 8
        range 4 16
        help
            The DSP engine maintains a fixed pool of output frames in PSRAM.
            Consumers retain frames via dsp_frame_retain(); the frame returns
            to the pool when all consumers release it.  Increase if consumers
            are slow (e.g. HTTP chunked transfer) to avoid dropped frames.

endmenu
